  "title": "The Huntington Unveils Century-First Rebrand by Base Design, Ushering in Era of Integration and Modernization",
  "publishedAt": "2026-01-16T16:20:03.982Z",
  "generatedAt": "2026-01-16T16:20:03.982Z",
  "totalSources": 10,
  "sections": [
    {
      "id": "section-0",
      "paragraphs": [
        {
          "id": "para-0-0",
          "content": "The Huntington Library, Art Museum, and Botanical Gardens in San Marino, California, launched its first comprehensive rebranding in over 100 years, designed by Base Design as part of the \"One Huntington\" strategic plan. The new identity simplifies the name to \"The Huntington\" and features a pared-back **'H' monogram** with stylized pillars flanking a gem-like center, replacing an ornate botanical-heavy version. This positions the institution as a \"hidden gem\" rooted in California yet framed for global appeal, emphasizing unity across its library, art, and gardens.",
          "citations": [
            {
              "primarySource": {
                "id": "source-1",
                "name": "BP&O",
                "url": "https://bpando.org/2026/01/15/the-huntington-museum-branding-by-base-design/",
                "favicon": "https://www.google.com/s2/favicons?domain=bpando.org&sz=32",
                "title": "The Huntington by Base Design"
              },
              "additionalCount": 1,
              "additionalSources": [
                {
                  "id": "source-2",
                  "name": "finebooksmagazine",
                  "url": "https://finebooksmagazine.com/fine-books-news/huntington-library-announces-modernization-plans",
                  "favicon": "https://www.google.com/s2/favicons?domain=finebooksmagazine.com&sz=32",
                  "title": "The Huntington by Base Design"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "para-0-1",
          "content": "The rebrand supports broader ambitions, including a spring 2026 groundbreaking for the 83,000-square-foot Library/Art Building (LAB) renovation led by RAMSA architects. This project will house over eight linear miles of collections and 38,000 works on paper, backed by a $126.6 million campaign with over $100 million raised. It aligns with 2026 exhibitions like Edmund de Waal's installations and Mercedes Dorame's Tongva-inspired show, fostering cross-disciplinary discovery.",
